.NET Framework 3.5.name: VRTK_UIPointer
.NET Framework 3.5.summary: The UI Pointer provides a mechanism for interacting with Unity UI elements on a world canvas. The UI Pointer can be attached to any game object the same way in which a Base Pointer can be and the UI Pointer also requires a controller to initiate the pointer activation and pointer click states.
.NET Framework 3.5.remarks:
The simplest way to use the UI Pointer is to attach the script to a game controller along with a Simple Pointer as this provides visual feedback as to where the UI ray is pointing.

 The UI pointer is activated via the `Pointer` alias on the `Controller Events` and the UI pointer click state is triggered via the `UI Click` alias on the `Controller Events`.
.NET Framework 3.5.example: VRTK/Examples/034_Controls_InteractingWithUnityUI uses the VRTK_UIPointer script on the right Controller to allow for the interaction with Unity UI elements using a Simple Pointer beam. The left Controller controls a Simple Pointer on the headset to demonstrate gaze interaction with Unity UI elements.

methods.name: IsActivationButtonPressed()
methods.summary: The IsActivationButtonPressed method is used to determine if the configured activation button is currently in the active state.
methods.returns: Returns true if the activation button is active.

methods.name: IsSelectionButtonPressed()
methods.summary: The IsSelectionButtonPressed method is used to determine if the configured selection button is currently in the active state.
methods.returns: Returns true if the selection button is active.

PointerActive()
methods.summary: The PointerActive method determines if the ui pointer beam should be active based on whether the pointer alias is being held and whether the Hold Button To Use parameter is checked.
methods.returns: Returns true if the ui pointer should be currently active.

methods.name: RemoveEventSystem()
methods.summary: The RemoveEventSystem resets the Unity EventSystem back to the original state before the VRTK_VRInputModule was swapped for it.

methods.name: SetEventSystem(EventSystem eventSystem)
methods.summary: The SetEventSystem method is used to set up the global Unity event system for the UI pointer. It also handles disabling the existing Standalone Input Module that exists on the EventSystem and adds a custom VRTK Event System VR Input component that is required for interacting with the UI with VR inputs.
methods.returns: A custom input module that is used to detect input from VR pointers.

params.value: The global Unity event system to be used by the UI pointers.

methods.name: ValidClick(bool checkLastClick, bool lastClickState)
methods.summary: The ValidClick method determines if the UI Click button is in a valid state to register a click action.
methods.returns: Returns true if the UI Click button is in a valid state to action a click, returns false if it is not in a valid state.

params.value: If this is true then the last frame's state of the UI Click button is also checked to see if a valid click has happened.
This determines what the last frame's state of the UI Click button should be in for it to be a valid click.
